Q4.4: some expressions and most pronouns were not translated correctly

Overall, I thought the subtitles were appropriate and well written, however, there was 1 instance that I noted: When Augustin is talking to Mr. Nelson about going on a date with Andrea, he says something like 'in reparation for not meeting her,' reading 'in reparation' took me out of the story for a few seconds. I understood what it meant but because it is a bit unusual in colloquial speech, I think it looked slightly odd.

Nothing difficult to understand, but the computer often chose the wrong pronouns. Third person singular verbs were often attributed to "he" when the implied subject was "ella" or "Usted". Might have been confusing if I didn't know enough Spanish to tell that this was happening. Then a number of expressions were translated too literally rather than idiomatically: "ugly with a capital EFE"; "colluding"; "sync", "as God commands".
